INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (225,1,'2025-03-14 07:46:40','2025-03-14 07:46:40','<!-- wp:query {\"queryId\":24,\"query\":{\"perPage\":10,\"pages\":0,\"offset\":0,\"postType\":\"post\",\"order\":\"desc\",\"orderBy\":\"date\",\"author\":\"\",\"search\":\"\",\"exclude\":[],\"sticky\":\"\",\"inherit\":false,\"taxQuery\":null,\"parents\":[]},\"metadata\":{\"categories\":[\"posts\"],\"patternName\":\"twentytwentyfive/template-query-loop\",\"name\":\"List of posts, 1 column\"},\"align\":\"full\",\"layout\":{\"type\":\"default\"}} -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-query alignfull\"><!-- wp:post-template {\"align\":\"full\",\"layout\":{\"type\":\"default\"}} -->\n<!-- wp:group {\"align\":\"full\",\"style\":{\"spacing\":{\"padding\":{\"top\":\"var:preset|spacing|60\",\"bottom\":\"var:preset|spacing|60\"}}},\"layout\":{\"type\":\"constrained\"}} -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-group alignfull\" style=\"padding-top:var(--wp--preset--spacing--60);padding-bottom:var(--wp--preset--spacing--60)\"><!-- wp:heading {\"textAlign\":\"center\"} -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading has-text-align-center\"><strong>This treadmill is alright even though its more than a grand(RIP bank account)#KindOfWorthIt!</strong></h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":223,\"sizeSlug\":\"full\",\"linkDestination\":\"none\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-full\"><img src=\"http://localhost:10011/wp-content/uploads/2025/03/BFBXT8J-1.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-223\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>\"Iâ€™ve been using this treadmill for a few months now, and overall, itâ€™sâ€¦ alright. For a machine that costs over $1,000, I expected a bit more, but it does the job. The DualTrackâ„¢ LCD displays are a standout featureâ€”theyâ€™re easy to read and make it simple to track my speed, distance, time, and calories burned. The 26 built-in workout programs are a nice touch, offering a good mix of options for cardio, strength, and interval training. Iâ€™ve tried a few of them, and they definitely keep my workouts from getting boring.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The speed range (0â€“12 mph) and motorized incline (up to 15%) are solid features. I mostly use it for running, and it handles well at higher speeds, though I noticed it can get a bit noisy when pushing past 10 mph. The incline is smooth and adds a nice challenge to my workouts. I also appreciate the media shelf and USB charging portâ€”itâ€™s convenient for watching videos or listening to music while I run, and I donâ€™t have to worry about my phone dying mid-workout.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The JRNY compatibility is a plus, and I like that I can access essential workouts without a subscription. The 2-month free trial for new members is a decent perk, though I havenâ€™t fully explored all the appâ€™s features yet. The included 5kHz heart rate chest strap is a nice bonusâ€”itâ€™s more accurate than the hand sensors, and Iâ€™ve been using it to monitor my heart rate during intense sessions.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>That said, while itâ€™s a decent treadmill, I canâ€™t say itâ€™s blown me away for the price. Itâ€™s not bad, but itâ€™s not amazing eitherâ€”just alright. The build quality is good, but not premium, and Iâ€™ve had a few minor issues with the belt alignment that required adjustments. If youâ€™re looking for something reliable with a few extra features, itâ€™s worth considering, but donâ€™t expect anything groundbreaking. Itâ€™s a solid mid-range treadmill, but Iâ€™m not sure itâ€™s the best value for over $1,000.\"</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Blog Post By:</strong> Thomas Maxie</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Date of Post:</strong> March 6, 2025</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Likes:</strong> 12â¬†ï¸ <strong>Dislikes:</strong> 1â¬‡ï¸</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragra